{{Jurassic}} The '''Aalenian''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|ɑː|ˈ|l|iː|n|i|ə|n}}) is a subdivision of the [[Middle Jurassic]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]]/[[series (stratigraphy)|series]] of the [[geologic timescale]] that extends from about 174.1 [[annum|Ma]] to about 170.3 Ma (million years ago). It was preceded by the [[Toarcian]] and succeeded by the [[Bajocian]].<ref>See Gradstein ''et al.'' (2004) for a detailed version of the geologic timescale</ref>
==Stratigraphic definitions== The Aalenian takes its name from the town of [[Aalen]], some 70&nbsp;km east of [[Stuttgart]] in [[Germany]]. The town lies at the southwestern end of the [[Jura mountains|Frankischer Jura]]. The name Aalenian was introduced in scientific literature by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] geologist [[Karl Mayer-Eymar]] in 1864.
[[File:Aalenian GSSP - Golden spike ceremony - Fuentelsaz, Guadalajara, Spain 08.jpg|thumb|The Aalenian GSSP in Spain]] The base of the Aalenian is defined as the place in the stratigraphic column where the [[ammonite]] [[genus]] ''[[Leioceras]]'' first appears. The global reference profile ([[Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point|GSSP]]) is located 500 meters north of the village of [[Fuentelsaz]] in the [[Spain|Spanish]] [[Guadalajara (province)|province of Guadalajara]].<ref>Cresta ''et al.'' (2001)</ref> The top of the Aalenian (the base of the Bajocian) is at the first appearance of ammonite genus ''[[Hyperlioceras]]''.
In the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys domain]], the Aalenian contains four ammonite [[biozone]]s: *zone of ''[[Graphoceras|Graphoceras concavum]]'' *zone of ''[[Brasilia (ammonite)|Brasilia bradfordensis]]'' *zone of ''[[Ludwigia murchisonae]]'' *zone of ''Leioceras opalinum''
