In [[Greek mythology]], the '''Ionides'''{{Pronunciation-needed}} were a sisterhood of water [[nymph]]s. Their individual names were '''Calliphaea''', '''Synallasis''' (or Synallaxis), '''Pegaea''' and '''Iasis'''.

The Ionides dwelt at [[Elis]], where they had a sanctuary near a spring flowing into River [[River god|Cytherus]], and were said to have the power to cure all kinds of disease. Their surname was thought to have come from the name of Ion, son of Gargettus.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 6. 22. 7</ref>

